        <div class="block text-block"><p><strong>By Nancy Flores</strong><br/>
American-Statesman Staff<br/>
<a href="mailto:nflores@statesman.com">nflores@statesman.com</a> </p><aside class="scrollmation-inline " data-copy-element data-media-ratio="1.4" data-resize-element=".scrollmation-two-column .secondary-column" data-scrollmation-slide>
<img alt="Ezekiel “Zeke” Castro, director of the mariachi ensemble at the University of Texas at Austin, first stepped into UT’s music building as a fledgling musician at the age of 9. He's now considered a trailblazer in the city's mariachi music scene. Above, he introduces a song and encourages the audience to dance during a performance at The Clay Pit on May 8. (Photo by Tom McCarthy Jr./For American-Statesman)" class="inline-image edit-image-button" data-min-width-1401="./media/scrollmation-elrey-mr_cfckbov.jpg" src="./media/scrollmation-elrey-lr_oryy0ww.jpg">
<p class="caption"><em>Ezekiel “Zeke” Castro, director of the mariachi ensemble at the University of Texas at Austin, first stepped into UT’s music building as a fledgling musician at the age of 9. He's now considered a trailblazer in the city's mariachi music scene. Above, he introduces a song and encourages the audience to dance during a performance at The Clay Pit on May 8.</em> <br/><br/><em>(Photo by Tom McCarthy Jr./For American-Statesman)</em></p>
</img></aside>

<p>On their last performance of the spring semester, members of the <a href="https://www.facebook.com/utmariachiparedes">University of Texas’ Mariachi Paredes de Tejastitlán</a> took their places before an audience at the Clay Pit Indian restaurant.  </p>
<p>Mariachi director Ezekiel “Zeke” Castro, sporting a burnt-orange Bevo bow tie and a mariachi outfit matching his students, stood off to one side with his chest puffed out like a proud papa. He’d been preparing the students since January, watching their technique improve and their confidence grow. Now, they were belting out traditional songs like “El Son de la Negra” with pride and charisma.  </p>
<p>Between songs, Castro grabbed the microphone, explaining historical tidbits about each mariachi tune and pumping up the crowd. “‘El Rey’ is one of my favorite songs,” Castro told the audience with a smile. “And if you’re wondering why, well, it’s because that’s me — The King.”  </p>
<p>With a lifetime of musical experience, Castro, 75, deserves to call himself “the king” if he wants.  </p>
<p>In 1980, he launched the Austin Independent School District’s first mariachi program. Eventually, the mini mariachi musicians graduated and many of them went on to lift Austin’s music scene by joining or launching their own professional mariachi groups and carving out a more prominent place for mariachi music in the city.  </p></div><figure class="block quote-block">
<blockquote>
<p>“‘El Rey’ is one of my favorite songs,” Castro told the audience with a smile. “And if you’re wondering why, well, it’s because that’s me — The King.”  </p>
</blockquote>
</figure><div class="block text-block"><p>Today, Castro’s career has come full circle. At UT, he’s molding a new generation of college students at the same university that filled him with wonderment for music when he was only 9. That’s when Castro first stepped into UT’s music building as a fledgling musician. At the time, he never imagined his experience there would shape the rest of his life.  </p></div>
      
