        <div class="block text-block"><p>“Would you like to study the violin?” the teacher asked Castro, then an elementary student at the Palm School, which served East Austin children for 84 years until its closure in 1976.  </p><aside class="scrollmation-inline portrait-image" data-copy-element data-media-ratio="0.714285714286" data-resize-element=".scrollmation-two-column .secondary-column" data-scrollmation-slide>
<img alt="Castro credits his grandfather, Ezequiel Acevedo, for his musical talents. Acevedo, pictured here circa 1915, was a musician in Lockhart. (Photo contributed by Zeke Castro)" class="inline-image edit-image-button" data-min-width-1401="./media/scrollmation-grandfather-mr_7gthrbu.jpg" src="./media/scrollmation-grandfather-lr_eotwkmg.jpg">
<p class="caption"><em>Castro credits his grandfather, Ezequiel Acevedo, for his musical talents. Acevedo, pictured here circa 1915, was a musician in Lockhart.</em> <br/><br/><em>(Photo contributed by Zeke Castro)</em></p>
</img></aside>

<p>It was 1948, three years after the conclusion of World War II, and many orchestra teachers who had gone off to war never came back. With the future of American orchestras in jeopardy, UT launched the Junior String Project, a program that still exists today as the <a href="https://stringproject.music.utexas.edu/">UT String Project</a> and trains university students to become orchestra teachers and also develops young string players.  </p>
<p>Three times a week, Castro walked from Palm School — now county offices at East Cesar Chavez Street and Interstate 35 — to Sixth and Brazos streets to pick up his violin and music at his mother’s job at Gellman’s department store. The fourth-grader would then catch a bus and head to the UT campus.  </p>
<p>Music was in Castro’s blood. He never met his grandfather, Ezequiel Acevedo, but Castro credits him for his musical abilities. Aside from being a barber — “People had to do what they had to do to put beans on the table,” Castro says — his grandfather was also a musician in Lockhart.  </p>
<p>Castro keeps a photo of his grandfather’s all-cousin band, and laughs when he remembers that the bass drum read “Lockhart Mexican Band.”  </p></div>
      
