<div id="scrollmation-two-column-4032" class="section section-scrollmation scrollmation-two-column section-two-column-4032" data-possible-scrollmation data-scrollmation-container="#scrollmation-two-column-4032" data-viewport-height data-viewport-height-property="min-height">
  <div class="two-column-grid">
    <div class="column column-left main-column scrollmation-text">
      
        <div class="block text-block"><p>While Texas cities like San Antonio led the way in establishing student mariachi programs in the 1970s, Austin was slower to embrace the art form in schools.  </p><aside class="scrollmation-inline " data-copy-element data-media-ratio="3.5" data-resize-element=".scrollmation-two-column .secondary-column" data-scrollmation-slide>
<img alt="After graduating from UT, Castro performed with the Austin Symphony, pictured here in fall 1960, as well as symphonies in Georgia and California. (Photo contributed by Zeke Castro)" class="inline-image edit-image-button" data-min-width-1401="./media/scrollmation-symphony-mr_3erssnr.jpg" src="./media/scrollmation-symphony-lr_3qqe0rk.jpg">
<p class="caption"><em>After graduating from UT, Castro performed with the Austin Symphony, pictured here in fall 1960, as well as symphonies in Georgia and California.</em> <br/><br/><em>(Photo contributed by Zeke Castro)</em></p>
</img></aside>

<p>In 1972, Gus Garcia — who would later go on to become mayor of Austin — became the first Hispanic to serve on the Austin ISD board of trustees at a time when the student body was about 15 percent Hispanic. Today, Hispanic students make up about 60 percent of the student body.  </p>
<p>Throughout Garcia’s term, which lasted until 1978, he was told that there weren’t any qualified teachers in Austin to teach mariachi. “My answer was, ‘Well, why don’t we find one?” Garcia says.  </p>
<p>In 1979, AISD finally found their guy.  </p><aside class="scrollmation-inline portrait-image" data-copy-element data-media-ratio="0.714285714286" data-resize-element=".scrollmation-two-column .secondary-column" data-scrollmation-slide>
<img alt="Ollin Chavez plays the violin in Mariachi Amor, an Austin-based mariachi band.(Photos by Kelly West/American-Statesman)" class="inline-image edit-image-button" data-min-width-1401="./media/scrollmation-violin-mr_mwtfxku.jpg" src="./media/scrollmation-violin-lr_ttwuwuc.jpg">
<p class="caption"><em>Ollin Chavez plays the violin in Mariachi Amor, an Austin-based mariachi band.</em><br/><br/><em>(Photos by Kelly West/American-Statesman)</em></p>
</img></aside>

<p>After graduating from UT, Castro spent nearly 20 years outside of Texas, working with student orchestras and playing in symphonies in Georgia and California. Castro began playing mariachi music at age 30 while living in California. “That’s late,” Castro says. “But you have to remember I was in the string project from day one, taught to read music, to just play those dots … but mariachi music comes from inside, comes from your heart and soul. That’s what makes mariachi.”  </p>
<p><em>Listen to an excerpt from our interview with Castro below:</em> </p></div><div class="block html-block"><!-- You can use this Custom HTML block to put in your own HTML -->
<!-- Common uses for this block are videos & advertisements -->
<!-- CSS should go in the CUSTOM CSS panel on the left -->
<div>
<iframe frameborder="no" height="450" scrolling="no" src="https://w.soundcloud.com/player/?url=https%3A//api.soundcloud.com/tracks/207526821&amp;auto_play=false&amp;hide_related=false&amp;show_comments=true&amp;show_user=true&amp;show_reposts=false&amp;visual=true" width="100%"></iframe>
</div>
</div><div class="block text-block"><p>Castro was recruited as an AISD music educator, and in 1980 was challenged to start mariachi programs both at Fulmore Middle School and Travis High School simultaneously. He’d already been teaching at Fulmore, and so he knew students, teachers and the principal, which made the task a little less daunting. “But at Travis, I had no idea even where the band hall was,” Castro says.  </p><aside class="scrollmation-inline portrait-image" data-copy-element data-media-ratio="0.714285714286" data-resize-element=".scrollmation-two-column .secondary-column" data-scrollmation-slide>
<img alt="Trumpet player Alex Ramirez, founder of Mariachi Amor, was part of Castro’s first mariachi class at Fulmore Middle School. Now, he’s a professional mariachi musician. " class="inline-image edit-image-button" data-min-width-1401="./media/scrollmation-trumpet-mr_ijtfvfa.jpg" src="./media/scrollmation-trumpet-lr_rrtm0eq.jpg">
<p class="caption"><em>Trumpet player Alex Ramirez, founder of Mariachi Amor, was part of Castro’s first mariachi class at Fulmore Middle School. Now, he’s a professional mariachi musician.</em> </p>
</img></aside>

<p>The plan? Make mariachi players out of the middle school students, who would bring their talents to Travis the following year and form a mariachi program that would blaze a trail in Austin.  </p></div><div class="block media-block media-block-youtube">
<div class="inline-media">
<div class="inline-youtube">
<iframe allowfullscreen frameborder="0" height="315" id="scrollmation-two-column-4032-block-4" src="//www.youtube.com/embed/If6dzvh2_v4?enablejsapi=1&amp;rel=0" width="560"></iframe>
</div>
<p class="media-block-caption caption">
<b>Watch the video above to hear a mariachi violin.</b>
</p>
</div>
</div><div class="block text-block"><p>Castro, with the help of Fulmore band teacher Dorothy Farmer, assembled about 24 students at the middle school. But playing in band or orchestra wasn’t the same as playing with a mariachi group. Some of the students had never even seen some of the instruments that make up a mariachi band.  </p>
<p>Violin and trumpet players jumped onboard. But where were players of the deep-bodied bass guitarrón and the vihuela, a smaller and louder version of the guitar, going to come from?  </p><aside class="scrollmation-inline " data-copy-element data-media-ratio="1.4" data-resize-element=".scrollmation-two-column .secondary-column" data-scrollmation-slide>
<img alt="Marjorie Gonzales Chavez plays the guitarrón, which serves as the bass in a mariachi band." class="inline-image edit-image-button" data-min-width-1401="./media/scrollmation-guitarron-mr_4nmo2ha.jpg" src="./media/scrollmation-guitarron-lr_gayxzdk.jpg">
<p class="caption"><em>Marjorie Gonzales Chavez plays the guitarrón, which serves as the bass in a mariachi band.</em></p>
</img></aside>
</div><div class="block media-block media-block-youtube">
<div class="inline-media">
<div class="inline-youtube">
<iframe allowfullscreen frameborder="0" height="315" id="scrollmation-two-column-4032-block-6" src="//www.youtube.com/embed/BAPmh39zuuc?enablejsapi=1&amp;rel=0" width="560"></iframe>
</div>
<p class="media-block-caption caption">
<b>Watch the video above to hear a mariachi trumpet.</b>
</p>
</div>
</div><div class="block text-block"><p>“Let’s pick out our best musicians and we’ll teach them how to play guitar,” Castro told Farmer. Castro worked with the new guitar players, watching them carefully over weeks and eventually transitioned some students to play the vihuela, others the guitarrón, and a few stayed on guitar.  </p>
<p>When most of the Fulmore students came over to Travis the following year, “it turned the world upside down as far as Austin is concerned,” Castro says. “We’d play one note and all the gritos would start. The community opened their hearts to my groups, and that program shot up like a rocket in Austin.”  </p></div><div class="block media-block media-block-youtube">
<div class="inline-media">
<div class="inline-youtube">
<iframe allowfullscreen frameborder="0" height="315" id="scrollmation-two-column-4032-block-8" src="//www.youtube.com/embed/TGquOvSWZlY?enablejsapi=1&amp;rel=0" width="560"></iframe>
</div>
<p class="media-block-caption caption">
<b>Watch the video above to hear a mariachi </b><i style="line-height: normal;"><b>guitarrón</b></i><b>.</b>
</p>
</div>
</div><div class="block heading-block"><h3><strong>MARIACHI MUSIC AT A GLANCE</strong></h3></div><div class="block text-block"><p><em>Mariachi music, as it is known today, has roots that date back to the 19th century. Jalisco is often credited as the birthplace of mariachi. In the late 1800s, Castro says, mariachi groups moved out of the Jalisco area and traveled to Mexico City, where they were exposed to different musical genres from various regions and began to incorporate other styles of music like the polka into the mariachi sound.</em> </p></div><div class="block media-block media-block-youtube">
<div class="inline-media">
<div class="inline-youtube">
<iframe allowfullscreen frameborder="0" height="315" id="scrollmation-two-column-4032-block-11" src="//www.youtube.com/embed/jhFUP8y1-CM?enablejsapi=1&amp;rel=0" width="560"></iframe>
</div>
<p class="media-block-caption caption">
<b>Watch the video above to hear the mariachi style of <span style="line-height: normal;">singing</span></b><b>. </b><br/><b><br/></b><br/><b>The youngest singer above, 4-year-old Xochi Chavez, has also been playing violin for 8 months. Watch her play in the video below.</b>
</p>
</div>
</div><div class="block text-block"><p><em>Today, typical mariachi instruments include the vihuela (a smaller version of the guitar), guitarrón (which serves as the bass), guitar, violin and trumpet. The vihuela and guitarrón are native Mexican instruments, while the rest are European. The harp formed part of the mariachi’s original instrumentation until about the 1890s when the guitarrón’s powerful sound eventually replaced it, Castro says. “Now the harp is making a comeback,” he says. “In the age of electronics, every instrument can have a microphone. If a harp can be amplified, then it fits right in.”</em> </p></div>
      
    </div>

