>
  

  <div class="main-column">
    <div class="block heading-block"><h3><strong>Call me Mr. Castro</strong></h3></div><div class="block text-block"><p>Alex Ramirez may be 48 years old, but that doesn’t stop him from calling the mariachi master “Mr. Castro.” “I feel he’s earned it,” says Ramirez, part of Castro’s first mariachi class at Fulmore.  </p>
<p>Many other former students do the same.  </p>
<p>“They are adults now,” Castro says. “Some of them have their own children. But when I speak to them, it’s, ‘Hi, Mr. Castro.’”  </p>
<p>Ramirez, who once played trumpet in Castro’s mariachi class, now volunteers as a trumpet coach with UT’s Castro-directed Mariachi Paredes de Tejastitlán, and so still works closely with his mentor. He also continues to play the trumpet, but for his own professional group, Mariachi Amor.  </p>
<p>After participating in Castro’s inaugural mariachi middle school and high school programs, Ramirez went on to play with legendary Mexican-American musician Manuel “Cowboy” Donley. Later, he produced a sold-out mariachi show at the Paramount Theatre, which helped pave the way for other Hispanic cultural programming at the venue.  </p>
<p>Today, Ramirez estimates there are about a dozen professional mariachi groups in Austin. Some of them, like <a href="https://www.facebook.com/mariachiamor">Mariachi Amor,</a> were launched by or have featured Castro’s former students. “For awhile in Austin, whenever I went out and there was a mariachi playing, invariably I’d find one of my students,” Castro says.  </p></div>
