        <div class="block text-block"><p>It was only the second day of class for Castro’s UT mariachi ensemble students, but already they were rehearsing for their first gig in San Antonio. Castro sat at a piano in the large university choral rehearsal room and his students formed a semicircle around him with their instruments and sang the lyrics to the “El Son de la Negra.”  </p><aside class="scrollmation-inline " data-copy-element data-media-ratio="1.4" data-resize-element=".scrollmation-two-column .secondary-column" data-scrollmation-slide>
<img alt="Castro helps University of Texas at Austin sophomore Job Ramirez adjust his bow before a performance at The Clay Pit on May 8. (Photos by Tom McCarthy Jr./For American-Statesman)" class="inline-image edit-image-button" data-min-width-1401="./media/scrollmation-family3-mr_clrla9e.jpg" src="./media/scrollmation-family3-lr_bnt3qae.jpg">
<p class="caption"><em>Castro helps University of Texas at Austin sophomore Job Ramirez adjust his bow before a performance at The Clay Pit on May 8. (Photos by Tom McCarthy Jr./For American-Statesman)</em></p>
</img></aside>

<p>“That was better, but give me more volume,” Castro says.  </p>
<p>Returning Mariachi Paredes de Tejastitlán students have begun to realize Castro’s deep contributions to Austin’s mariachi history.  </p>
<p>“I didn’t think of him as a well-known person,” says biochemistry major Derick Sanchez, 21, who plays the vihuela. “But then he brought in a song that he wrote called, ‘La Calle Ancha,’”Sanchez says. <a href="https://shar.es/1rFkGA">La Calle Ancha</a>, as it was known to Spanish speakers, referred to East Avenue, the old, wide street that Interstate 35 replaced in 1962.  </p><aside class="scrollmation-inline " data-copy-element data-media-ratio="1.4" data-resize-element=".scrollmation-two-column .secondary-column" data-scrollmation-slide>
<img alt="Karla Rios, a sophomore at UT, sings the lead vocal of a song at The Clay Pit." class="inline-image edit-image-button" data-min-width-1401="./media/scrollmation-family2-mr_zh9zauy.jpg" src="./media/scrollmation-family2-lr_jsdotox.jpg">
<p class="caption"><em>Karla Rios, a sophomore at UT, sings the lead vocal of a song at The Clay Pit.</em></p>
</img></aside>

<p>Castro says he knows his UT students, who have varying majors, will likely not pursue music as a profession, but he still wants to help them appreciate the music, enjoy and play it throughout their lives no matter what paths they take.  </p>
<p>Sanchez says the students in the mariachi group end up becoming “a small family,” and mariachi’s actually helped him learn Spanish and reconnect with his heritage.  </p>
<p>Karla Rios, a vocalist and violin player in the class, says mariachi helps her unplug from her hectic academic schedule. “I mean, we throw gritos (mariachi shouts) in here,” she says with a laugh.  </p><aside class="scrollmation-inline " data-copy-element data-media-ratio="1.4" data-resize-element=".scrollmation-two-column .secondary-column" data-scrollmation-slide>
<img alt="John Gonzales, left, a sophomore at UT, and Ramirez perform with the university's mariachi ensemble at The Clay Pit." class="inline-image edit-image-button" data-min-width-1401="./media/scrollmation-family1-mr_j3cstgv.jpg" src="./media/scrollmation-family1-lr_cuzaktm.jpg">
<p class="caption"><em>John Gonzales, left, a sophomore at UT, and Ramirez perform with the university's mariachi ensemble at The Clay Pit.</em></p>
</img></aside>
</div><figure class="block quote-block">
<blockquote>
<p>Castro says he knows his UT students, who have varying majors, will likely not pursue music as a profession, but he still wants to help them appreciate the music, enjoy and play it throughout their lives no matter what paths they take.  </p>
</blockquote>
</figure><div class="block text-block"><p>Castro’s mariachi class meets for three hours, but it’s only once a week, which means each class equals crucial rehearsal time.  </p>
<p>“Mexicooo, Mexicooo,” the students sing out.  </p>
<p>“When we get to the last ‘Mexico,’ it’s got to be earth shattering,” Castro tells the students. “We need to wake up all those in the audience who were taking naps.”  </p></div>
      
