        <div class="block heading-block"><h3><strong>Keeping the fire going</strong></h3></div><aside class="scrollmation-inline " data-copy-element data-media-ratio="1.4" data-resize-element=".scrollmation-two-column .secondary-column" data-scrollmation-slide>
<img alt="The UT Viola Ensemble got an official sendoff from former Texas Governor Price Daniel in spring 1958. From left, Lee Kull, William Wilson, Karrell Johnson, Castro, Jim Pescor, Louis Guerrero and Frank Musick. (Photo contributed by Zeke Castro)" class="inline-image edit-image-button" data-min-width-1401="./media/scrollmation-price-mr_dqb7evx.jpg" src="./media/scrollmation-price-lr_e6vqall.jpg">
<p class="caption"><em>The UT Viola Ensemble got an official sendoff from former Texas Governor Price Daniel in spring 1958. From left, Lee Kull, William Wilson, Karrell Johnson, Castro, Jim Pescor, Louis Guerrero and Frank Musick.</em> <br/><br/><em>(Photo contributed by Zeke Castro)</em></p>
</img></aside>
<div class="block text-block"><p>Sometimes it’s hard for Castro to believe that the lessons he learned as a young boy continue to influence both his music and his teaching.  </p>
<p>Growing up, when Castro’s family moved from East Austin to a neighborhood near the old Mueller airport, he used to sit on the steps of the control tower and watch the planes arrive in and depart from Austin. “I’d never gone anywhere,” Castro says. “But I’d watch the planes come in and out.”  </p>
<p>When Castro finally did step onto a plane, it was music that took him to experience the world as a college freshman with the UT Viola Ensemble, for performances including one at New York City’s Carnegie Hall. Later, he also performed for President Jimmy Carter at the White House with the professional group Mariachi Estrella.  </p>
<p>Music also took his student mariachi groups across the country. Two years after Castro launched the Travis High School Mariachi Rebeldes del Sur, the students were invited to participate in the Fourth of July Parade in Washington, D.C., where they played their music on a float that rode down Constitution Avenue.  </p><aside class="scrollmation-inline " data-copy-element data-media-ratio="1.4" data-resize-element=".scrollmation-two-column .secondary-column" data-scrollmation-slide>
<img alt="Mariachi director Zeke Castro was invited to perform at the White House for President Jimmy Carter's National Salute to Congress in 1980. (Photo contributed by Zeke Castro)" class="inline-image edit-image-button" data-min-width-1401="./media/scrollmation-carters-mr_4spm37i.jpg" src="./media/scrollmation-carters-lr_rvprvme.jpg">
<p class="caption"><em>Mariachi director Zeke Castro was invited to perform at the White House for President Jimmy Carter's National Salute to Congress in 1980.</em> <br/><br/><em>(Photo contributed by Zeke Castro)</em></p>
</img></aside>

<p>Today, according to AISD, mariachi programs can be found at three high schools and one middle school.  </p>
<p>“I’ve never thought of myself as a pathfinder, but that’s the way it turned out,” Castro says. “My job is to light the fire, and then keep the fire for mariachi going.”  </p>
